00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.995
E

2
00:00:05.120 --> 00:00:05.837
(POLICE WHISTLE BLOWING)

3
00:00:06.400 --> 00:00:07.913
(ALARM RINGING)

4
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:09.832
(POLICE SIREN WAILING)

5
00:00:18.240 --> 00:00:20.197
(AMBULANCE SIREN WAILING)

6
00:01:01.240 --> 00:01:05.120
MAN: Police Constable Nicholas Angel.
Born and schooled in London.

7
00:01:05.200 --> 00:01:10.752
Graduated Canterbury University in 1993
with a double first in politics and sociology.

8
00:01:10.840 --> 00:01:13.116
Attended Hendon College of Police Training.

9
00:01:14.360 --> 00:01:16.920
Displayed great aptitude in field exercises.

10
00:01:19.280 --> 00:01:21.874
Notably, urban pacification and riot control.

11
00:01:22.400 --> 00:01:23.470
Back off!

12
00:01:23.560 --> 00:01:27.633
Academically excelled in theoretical
course work and final year examinations.

13
00:01:28.040 --> 00:01:29.951
Received the Baton of Honour.

14
00:01:30.040 --> 00:01:33.920
Graduated with distinction into
the Metropolitan Police Service.

15
00:01:34.360 --> 00:01:37.876
Quickly established an effectiveness
and popularity within the community.

16
00:01:38.240 --> 00:01:39.355
Use your brain.

17
00:01:39.760 --> 00:01:42.673
Proceeded to improve skill base
with courses in advanced driving

18
00:01:44.360 --> 00:01:46.556
and advanced cycling.

19
00:01:47.680 --> 00:01:51.150
Became heavily involved
in a number of extra vocational activities.

20
00:01:51.240 --> 00:01:54.119
To this day holds the Met record
for the 100 metre dash.

21
00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:59.836
in 2001 began active duty with
the renowned SO 19 armed response unit.

22
00:01:59.960 --> 00:02:04.113
Received a bravery award for efforts
in the resolution of Operation Crackdown.

23
00:02:04.600 --> 00:02:07.991
In the last 12 months
has received nine special commendations.

24
00:02:08.200 --> 00:02:11.113
Achieved the highest arrest record
for any officer in the Met.

25
00:02:11.200 --> 00:02:13.669
And sustained three injuries
in the line of duty.

26
00:02:13.760 --> 00:02:18.391
Most recently in December when wounded
by a man dressed as Father Christmas.

27
00:02:19.840 --> 00:02:24.835
E

28
00:02:24.960 --> 00:02:25.936
-Hello, Nicholas.
-Hello, Sergeant.

29
00:02:25.960 --> 00:02:26.936
-How's the hand?
-Still a bit stiff.

30
00:02:26.960 --> 00:02:27.950
It can get awfully hairy out there.

31
00:02:28.680 --> 00:02:32.150
I'm surprised you weren't snapped up
sooner for a nice desk job. That's what I did.

32
00:02:32.240 --> 00:02:34.436
I prefer to think my office is
out on the street.

33
00:02:34.520 --> 00:02:35.999
Indeed, you do.

34
00:02:36.280 --> 00:02:40.558
Your arrest record is 400% higher
than any other officer.

35
00:02:40.640 --> 00:02:45.077
Which is why it's high time
that such skills were put to better use.

36
00:02:46.920 --> 00:02:49.230
-We're making you Sergeant.
-I see.

37
00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:51.718
In Sandford, Gloucestershire.

38
00:02:51.800 --> 00:02:54.360
-In where, sorry?
-In Sandford, Gloucestershire.

39
00:02:54.440 --> 00:02:57.398
-That's in the country.
-Yes, lovely.

40
00:02:58.200 --> 00:02:59.952
Isn't there a Sergeant's position
here in London?

41
00:03:00.040 --> 00:03:01.189
No.

42
00:03:01.280 --> 00:03:03.476
-Can I remain here as a PC?
-No.

43
00:03:03.560 --> 00:03:05.870
-Do I have any choice in this?
-No.

44
00:03:06.920 --> 00:03:08.593
Sergeant, I kind of like it here.

45
00:03:08.680 --> 00:03:10.717
Well, you've always wanted
to transfer to the country.

46
00:03:10.800 --> 00:03:13.394
-In 20 years or so, yes.
-Well done, you.

47
00:03:13.880 --> 00:03:15.518
Hang on, I don't remember telling you that.

48
00:03:15.600 --> 00:03:17.591
Yes, you did. You said,

49
00:03:17.680 --> 00:03:20.559
"I'd love to settle down
in the country sometime, Janine."

50
00:03:21.880 --> 00:03:23.473
I'd like to talk to the Inspector.

51
00:03:23.560 --> 00:03:25.437
You can speak to the Inspector,
but I can promise you

52
00:03:25.520 --> 00:03:28.353
he will tell you
exactly the same thing as I have.

53
00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:33.311
-Hello, Nicholas. How's the hand?
-It's still a bit stiff.

54
00:03:33.400 --> 00:03:35.710
-And how are things at home?
-I'm sorry, sir?

55
00:03:35.800 --> 00:03:37.234
How's Janine?

56
00:03:38.840 --> 00:03:40.558
We're no longer together, sir.

57
00:03:40.640 --> 00:03:43.439
-Right. Then where are you living?
-He's staying at the Section House, sir.

58
00:03:43.520 --> 00:03:46.353
-With the recruits?
-Yes, he's living out of cardboard boxes.

59
00:03:46.440 --> 00:03:48.238
Well, then, you're packed already.

60
00:03:48.320 --> 00:03:51.153
Nicholas, we're offering you a smashing
position with a delightful cottage,

61
00:03:51.240 --> 00:03:54.517
in a lovely little place
that I think has won Village of the Year

62
00:03:54.600 --> 00:03:57.831
I don't know how many times.
It'll be good for you.

63
00:03:58.040 --> 00:04:01.351
-I don't really know what to say.
-Yes?

64
00:04:01.640 --> 00:04:03.153
Yes, thank you.

65
00:04:05.640 --> 00:04:07.358
No, I'm sorry. I'm gonna have to...

66
00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:10.239
-You want to take this higher?
-Yes, yes, I do.

67
00:04:10.320 --> 00:04:12.152
You want me to bother
the Chief Inspector with this?

68
00:04:12.240 --> 00:04:13.275
Yes.

69
00:04:13.360 --> 00:04:16.273
You want me to get the Chief Inspector
to come all the way down here?

70
00:04:16.360 --> 00:04:18.829
-Yes, I do.
-Okay.

71
00:04:19.720 --> 00:04:20.869
Kenneth!

72
00:04:21.360 --> 00:04:24.557
-Hello, Nicholas. How's the hand?
-Still a bit stiff.

73
00:04:24.920 --> 00:04:26.513
-Chief Inspector...
-Keep your seat.

74
00:04:26.600 --> 00:04:28.716
Now, I know what you're going to say,

75
00:04:28.800 --> 00:04:31.952
but the fact is,
you've been making us all look bad.

76
00:04:32.040 --> 00:04:33.075
I'm sorry, sir?

77
00:04:33.160 --> 00:04:34.559
Of course we all appreciate your efforts,

78
00:04:34.640 --> 00:04:37.109
but you've been rather
letting the side down.

79
00:04:37.200 --> 00:04:39.077
It's all about being a team player, Nicholas.

80
00:04:39.160 --> 00:04:41.071
You can't be the Sheriff of London.

81
00:04:41.160 --> 00:04:42.878
If we let you carry on running round town,

82
00:04:42.960 --> 00:04:46.635
you'll continue to be exceptional
and we can't have that.

83
00:04:46.720 --> 00:04:48.996
You'll put us all out of a job.

84
00:04:49.360 --> 00:04:50.998
With respect, sir.

85
00:04:51.080 --> 00:04:56.200
-You can't just make people disappear.
-Yes, I can. I'm the Chief Inspector.

86
00:04:56.880 --> 00:05:01.272
Well, however you spin this, there's
one thing you haven't taken into account.

87
00:05:01.400 --> 00:05:03.789
And that's what the "team”
is gonna make of this.

88
00:05:09.560 --> 00:05:14.555
E

89
00:05:14.640 --> 00:05:16.472
(CELL PHONE VIBRATING)

90
00:05:16.640 --> 00:05:17.789
(SIGHS)

91
00:05:18.680 --> 00:05:20.591
-Hello?
-ANGEL: Janine, it's me.

92
00:05:20.680 --> 00:05:22.637
I know. I'm at work.

93
00:05:22.720 --> 00:05:24.552
I know, I'm outside.

94
00:05:26.280 --> 00:05:27.953
What's the situation?

95
00:05:28.040 --> 00:05:30.998
You know the situation.
We've been over this.

96
00:05:31.080 --> 00:05:32.434
No, I... I meant here.

97
00:05:32.520 --> 00:05:35.034
Two people involved,
distinct signs of a struggle.

98
00:05:35.120 --> 00:05:36.269
Complete mess.

99
00:05:36.360 --> 00:05:39.318
-You are talking about here?
-Nicholas, what do you want?

100
00:05:39.400 --> 00:05:43.394
Well, I have something important to tell you
and I didn't wanna do it over the phone.

101
00:05:45.480 --> 00:05:48.199
Janine, I've been transferred.
I'm moving away for a while.

102
00:05:48.360 --> 00:05:49.395
I'm not Janine.

103
00:05:49.480 --> 00:05:50.675
(JANINE CLEARS THROAT)

104
00:05:50.760 --> 00:05:53.195
Janine, I've been transferred.
I'm moving away for a while.

105
00:05:53.280 --> 00:05:54.953
I know. Bob told me.

106
00:05:55.040 --> 00:05:56.155
Hello, there.

107
00:05:56.240 --> 00:05:58.231
Well, I wanted to tell you in person.

108
00:05:58.320 --> 00:06:00.357
And there's no reason
we can't be civil with each other.

109
00:06:00.440 --> 00:06:02.192
It's not that long ago
we were talking about getting married.

110
00:06:02.280 --> 00:06:05.079
Yes, but you were already married
to the force, weren't you?

111
00:06:05.160 --> 00:06:06.878
We're actually supposed to call it
"the service" now.

112
00:06:06.960 --> 00:06:09.554
Official vocab guidelines state
that "force" is too aggressive.

113
00:06:09.640 --> 00:06:11.358
See. It's only ever about the job.

114
00:06:11.440 --> 00:06:13.556
-It's all you care about.
-That's not true.

115
00:06:13.640 --> 00:06:16.439
No, you're right,
you do have that rubber plant.

116
00:06:16.520 --> 00:06:20.115
-It's a Japanese Peace Lily.
-You just can't switch off, Nicholas.

117
00:06:20.840 --> 00:06:25.789
And until you find a person you care
about more than your job, you never will.

118
00:06:26.680 --> 00:06:29.672
Besides, you were the one
who suggested we take a break.

119
00:06:29.760 --> 00:06:33.594
Yes, well,
guilty people often make the first move.

120
00:06:34.720 --> 00:06:36.677
Actually, there's something
I need to tell you.

121
00:06:36.760 --> 00:06:39.115
-You're seeing someone else.
-Yes. How did you...

122
00:06:39.200 --> 00:06:41.111
-Is it Bob?
-No.

123
00:06:41.200 --> 00:06:44.556
Does Bob look like
the kind of person I'd go out with?

124
00:06:44.640 --> 00:06:46.074
It's Dave.

125
00:06:46.160 --> 00:06:47.559
Hello, there.

126
00:06:48.440 --> 00:06:49.839
I see.

127
00:06:50.840 --> 00:06:52.274
Oh, Nicholas.

128
00:06:52.520 --> 00:06:55.034
You do realise that window
was broken from the inside?

129
00:06:55.480 --> 00:06:57.232
(HELICOPTER WHIRRING)

130
00:06:57.480 --> 00:07:02.475
E

131
00:07:02.600 --> 00:07:03.999
FRANK: Hello there, Nicholas,
Frank Butterman here, your new Inspector.

132
00:07:04.080 --> 00:07:07.152
I'm just calling with details
of your accommodation.

133
00:07:07.240 --> 00:07:10.198
We've got you a lovely little cottage
on Spencer Hill.

134
00:07:10.760 --> 00:07:13.070
Look forward to meeting you anon. Cheerio.

135
00:07:14.200 --> 00:07:17.192
Nicholas, Frank again.
One other thing about your cottage.

136
00:07:17.520 --> 00:07:18.590
It's not ready.

137
00:07:54.040 --> 00:07:55.269
(SNORING)

138
00:07:58.400 --> 00:08:01.916
It would appear the heavens have opened.

139
00:08:08.720 --> 00:08:12.554
-I was hoping to check in.
-Check in?

140
00:08:13.040 --> 00:08:15.270
But you've always been here.

141
00:08:15.640 --> 00:08:19.429
-Excuse me?
-Oh, I'm sorry.

142
00:08:19.520 --> 00:08:21.193
I thought you were my husband.

143
00:08:21.280 --> 00:08:23.874
-You must be Sergeant Angel.
-Yes, I am.

144
00:08:23.960 --> 00:08:27.112
I'm Joyce Cooper.
I trust you had a pleasant trip. Fascist.

145
00:08:27.600 --> 00:08:28.874
I beg your pardon?

146
00:08:28.960 --> 00:08:33.989
"System of Government characterised
by extreme dictatorship.” Seven across.

147
00:08:34.440 --> 00:08:38.798
-Oh, I see. It's "fascism."
-Fascism. Wonderful.

148
00:08:39.040 --> 00:08:43.273
Now, we've put you in the Castle Suite.
Bernard will escort you up there.

149
00:08:44.560 --> 00:08:48.440
Well, actually,
I could probably make my own way up. Hag.

150
00:08:48.880 --> 00:08:50.598
I beg your pardon?

151
00:08:50.680 --> 00:08:54.310
"Evil old woman considered
frightful or ugly." It's 12 down.

152
00:08:54.560 --> 00:08:56.949
Oh, bless you.

153
00:09:40.600 --> 00:09:44.070
-Pint of lager, please, Mary.
-MARY: Right you are, my love.

154
00:09:44.560 --> 00:09:46.233
Yes, sir, what can I get you?

155
00:09:46.320 --> 00:09:51.030
Could I have a glass
of the cranberry juice, please?

156
00:09:51.120 --> 00:09:52.349
Certainly.

157
00:09:52.440 --> 00:09:55.751
Now, you wouldn't, by any chance,
be the new policeman?

158
00:09:55.840 --> 00:09:57.797
Police officer, yes. I'm Nicholas Angel.

159
00:09:57.880 --> 00:10:00.633
-I'm Roy Porter. This is my wife Mary.
-Mary.

160
00:10:01.160 --> 00:10:02.355
MARY: Welcome to Sandford.

161
00:10:02.440 --> 00:10:03.874
If there's anything you need,
just let us know.

162
00:10:03.960 --> 00:10:07.112
Thank you. Could I borrow your newspaper?

163
00:10:07.200 --> 00:10:08.395
It's not ours, love.

164
00:10:08.480 --> 00:10:10.949
We're not big fans of the local fish wrapper,
are we, Mare?

165
00:10:11.040 --> 00:10:14.476
-They listed her age as 55.
-When I'm actually 53.

166
00:10:14.560 --> 00:10:15.755
Fifty-three.

167
00:10:15.840 --> 00:10:17.069
(GROANS)

168
00:10:17.160 --> 00:10:20.357
-Pint of lager, please, Mary.
-Right you are, my love.

169
00:10:24.920 --> 00:10:26.513
(PEOPLE LAUGHING)

170
00:10:51.880 --> 00:10:53.837
-Excuse me.
-What?

171
00:10:53.920 --> 00:10:56.230
-When's your birthday?
-Twenty-second of February.

172
00:10:56.320 --> 00:10:58.231
-What year?
-Every year.

173
00:10:58.320 --> 00:10:59.390
Get out.

174
00:11:00.520 --> 00:11:05.515
-When's your birthday?
-Eighth of May, 1969.

175
00:11:05.600 --> 00:11:07.318
-You're 377
-Yeah.

176
00:11:07.400 --> 00:11:08.470
Get out.

177
00:11:08.560 --> 00:11:09.630
When's your birthday?

178
00:11:09.720 --> 00:11:10.755
(STAMMERING)

179
00:11:10.840 --> 00:11:11.910
Out.

180
00:11:12.400 --> 00:11:15.438
-Is there a problem, Officer?
-Yes, there is, Mr Porter.

181
00:11:15.520 --> 00:11:18.194
It would appear a number
of your patrons are under age.

182
00:11:18.280 --> 00:11:20.874
Well, a few of them may be
a month or two south of proper.

183
00:11:20.960 --> 00:11:23.600
But if they're in here,
it stops them getting into trouble out there.

184
00:11:23.680 --> 00:11:25.830
Yeah, the way we see it,
it's all for the greater good.

185
00:11:25.920 --> 00:11:26.990
The greater good.

186
00:11:27.080 --> 00:11:31.199
Well, that's as may be,
but the law's the law and they'll have to go.

187
00:11:36.120 --> 00:11:38.953
-Another cranberry juice?
-I'm fine, thank you.

188
00:11:39.640 --> 00:11:44.635
E

189
00:11:51.960 --> 00:11:53.189
(CLANKING)

190
00:11:56.800 --> 00:11:58.313
(CLEARS THROAT)

191
00:11:59.600 --> 00:12:02.399
I hope you're not planning on driving that.

192
00:12:02.600 --> 00:12:03.670
No.

193
00:12:13.520 --> 00:12:14.749
(CAR ENGINE STARTS)

194
00:12:18.880 --> 00:12:21.759
Right. I'm taking you to the station.

195
00:12:23.240 --> 00:12:24.560
Where is it?

196
00:12:29.880 --> 00:12:30.995
(CLEARS THROAT)

197
00:12:31.080 --> 00:12:32.150
What?

198
00:12:42.320 --> 00:12:43.435
ANGEL: Move.

199
00:12:47.840 --> 00:12:49.956
"Nicholas Angel."

200
00:12:50.560 --> 00:12:53.439
-Oh, when did you start?
-Tomorrow.

201
00:12:53.880 --> 00:12:56.190
Well, I see you've already arrested
the whole village.

202
00:12:56.280 --> 00:12:57.395
Not exactly.

203
00:12:58.200 --> 00:13:00.999
-You in for the night?
-Go on, four's free.

204
00:13:01.080 --> 00:13:04.311
-Hey, now, I need to speak to him.
-He'll be no use till the morning.

205
00:13:04.400 --> 00:13:05.515
I see.

206
00:13:05.600 --> 00:13:08.479
You really want to process all this lot?

207
00:13:09.320 --> 00:13:11.755
-My pen's running out.
-Not a problem.

208
00:13:32.200 --> 00:13:37.195
E

209
00:13:49.160 --> 00:13:50.833
-Morning, Sergeant.
-Morning.

210
00:13:50.920 --> 00:13:52.035
Morning.

211
00:13:53.040 --> 00:13:54.155
Morning, Sergeant.

212
00:13:56.160 --> 00:13:57.958
Morning, Sergeant.

213
00:14:02.800 --> 00:14:04.916
-Lock me up.
-I'm sorry?

214
00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:07.037
I'm a slasher and I must be stopped.

215
00:14:07.880 --> 00:14:11.396
-You're a what?
-A slasher of prices.

216
00:14:12.840 --> 00:14:17.437
Just kidding. I'm Simon Skinner.
I run the local supermarché.

217
00:14:17.680 --> 00:14:20.991
Drop in and see me sometime.
My discounts are criminal.

218
00:14:21.360 --> 00:14:22.919
Catch me later!

219
00:14:24.840 --> 00:14:27.036
Morning, Sergeant.

220
00:14:32.320 --> 00:14:34.357
Morning, Sergeant.

221
00:14:37.840 --> 00:14:40.912
Could you tell the Inspector
I've arrived, please?

222
00:14:41.200 --> 00:14:42.474
No.

223
00:14:43.040 --> 00:14:44.235
Why?

224
00:14:44.640 --> 00:14:46.551
He's not in yet.

225
00:14:46.840 --> 00:14:49.195
-Well, how's our guest?
-Guest?

226
00:14:49.280 --> 00:14:53.717
-The inebriate in cell four.
-I don't know. Nobody tells me nothing.

227
00:14:58.960 --> 00:15:00.712
Can I get cell four open, please?

228
00:15:00.800 --> 00:15:02.791
Danny, can you open four?

229
00:15:05.240 --> 00:15:09.518
-He's gone.
-Oh, my God. Who's gone?

230
00:15:12.400 --> 00:15:16.394
-Why are you dressed like a police officer?
-Because I am one.

231
00:15:17.240 --> 00:15:19.550
Sergeant Angel, at last. Frank Butterman.

232
00:15:20.680 --> 00:15:23.638
- See you've already met my boy.
-Yes.

233
00:15:25.520 --> 00:15:28.672
FRANK: Do forgive me.
I'm something of a Wild West nut.

234
00:15:28.760 --> 00:15:32.913
Speaking of which, that was a fair
few outlaws you rounded up last night.

235
00:15:33.080 --> 00:15:34.593
Thank you, sir.

236
00:15:34.680 --> 00:15:39.390
I admire your enthusiasm
and far be it from me to stifle your flair,

237
00:15:39.480 --> 00:15:42.074
but this isn't London.
Oh, yes, please, Danny.

238
00:15:42.160 --> 00:15:43.230
With respect, sir,

239
00:15:43.320 --> 00:15:46.438
geographical location shouldn't factor
in the application of the law.

240
00:15:46.520 --> 00:15:47.749
No, thanks.

241
00:15:47.840 --> 00:15:51.595
Statistically, Sandford is
the safest village in the country.

242
00:15:51.680 --> 00:15:53.796
But that doesn't mean
it requires anything less

243
00:15:53.880 --> 00:15:56.235
than a careful and considered approach.

244
00:15:56.320 --> 00:15:59.119
